incurred in service. He attended Bowdoin College and lived most of his post-war life in New Hampshire. His military service continued the family pattern that included his grand-uncle William Adrian Ingersoll, USN paymaster, and Captain George Sumner Arnold, his paternal grandfather and commander of the New Haven Grays."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Woodbridge CT 1915 to Concord NH 2004","body":"Charles Ingersoll 'Ingy' Arnold was born July 14, 1915 in Woodbridge New Haven County Connecticut and died January 6, 2004 in Concord Merrimack County New Hampshire at age eighty-eight. He is buried at Old Hopkinton Cemetery Hopkinton New Hampshire. He married Dorothy Spoor of Pueblo Colorado in 1942 — she later served as Vice President of the Penny Pitou travel agency in Concord NH."}],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"military_service":[{"war":"World War II","war_id":"WAR002","side":"American","rank_start":"2nd Lieutenant","rank_end":"2nd Lieutenant","unit":"United States Army","service_years":"WWII","awards":["Purple Heart"],"notes":"2nd Lieutenant United States Army during World War II. Recipient of the Purple Heart for wounds received in service."}],"education":[{"school_name":"Bowdoin College","role":"student","degree":"BA","graduation_year":1939,"notes":"Class of 1939; Alpha Delta Phi fraternity; first freshman to play on varsity hockey team; later honored 1992 as \"Number One Hockey Fan.\" Only one Hooker-tree person currently documented at Bowdoin so no INST entry per §9 2+ rule."},{"school_name":"Yale University School of Forestry","role":"student","degree":"Master of Forestry","graduation_year":1941,"notes":"M.F. 1941"}],"career":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Charles Ingersoll Arnold","first_name":"Charles","last_name":"Arnold","middle_name":"Ingersoll","married_names":[],"nickname":"Ingy","gender":"male"},"slug":"charles-arnold-1915"},"HD5145":{"id":"HD5145","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":10,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker_bool":true},"parents":{"father_id":"I01307","mother_id":"HD5134"},"tags":["junior_league","mayflower_descendant"],"research_tags":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I01313","date_year":1937,"date_month":6,"date_day":19,"location_city":"New Haven","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1996,"children_ids":["HD5146"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"birth":{"year":1916,"country":"United States"},"death":{"year":2000,"age":84,"country":"United States"},"residence":{},"burial":{},"baptism":{},"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Mayflower Elder Brewster descent on father's side","body":"Justine Arnold was a documented descendant of Elder William Brewster — the senior elder of the Plymouth Colony Pilgrims who arrived on the Mayflower in 1620. The Brewster line came through her father Dr. Harold Sears Arnold's family. The Mayflower connection placed her in two of the most documented founding-era American ancestral lines: Brewster (Mayflower 1620) and Hooker (Hartford 1636) through her mother."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Yale Fine Arts student married fellow student","body":"Justine attended Mrs. Day's School in New Haven and the Yale School of Fine Arts. On June 19, 1937 at Christ Church New Haven, she married Edward Mortimer Linforth — also a Yale School of Fine Arts student and son of Professor Ivan M. Linforth of Berkeley California. Her cousin Leeanne Gwynne (the Portland piano teacher) was a flower girl at the wedding and her brother Ingersoll 'Ingy' Arnold served as an usher."}],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"military_service":[],"education":[],"career":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Justine Ingersoll Linforth","first_name":"Justine","last_name":"Linforth","maiden_name":"Arnold","middle_name":"Ingersoll","married_names":["Linforth"],"gender":"female"},"slug":"justine-linforth-1916"},"HD5138":{"id":"HD5138","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":10,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker_bool":true},"parents":{"father_id":"I01307","mother_id":"HD5134"},"tags":[],"research_tags":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"marriages":[],"number_of_marriages":0,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"birth":{"year":1920,"country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1985,"age":65,"country":"United States"},"residence":{},"burial":{},"baptism":{},"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"military_service":[],"education":[],"career":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Anne Esther Hunt","first_name":"Anne","last_name":"Hunt","maiden_name":"Arnold","middle_name":"Esther","married_names":["Hunt"],"gender":"female"},"slug":"anne-hunt-1920"},"HD5112":{"id":"HD5112","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":7,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker_bool":true},"parents":{"father_id":"HD0121","mother_id":"I01299"},"tags":["federal_judge","judge","lawyer","yale_graduate"],"research_tags":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I01302","date_year":1839,"end_type":"death","end_year":1860,"children_ids":["HD5129","HD5130","HD5131"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_blurb":"Judge, US District Court for the District of Connecticut","notable_category":["law"],"primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_A._Ingersoll","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"birth":{"year":1798,"month":10,"day":19,"city":"New Haven","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1860,"month":1,"day":12,"city":"New Haven","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States","age":61},"residence":{},"burial":{"plot_notes":"Grove Street Cemetery, New Haven CT"},"baptism":{},"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"law","header":"US federal judge nominated by President Pierce","body":"Charles Anthony Ingersoll served as a United States federal judge, nominated to the bench by President Franklin Pierce in the 1850s. The appointment placed him on the Connecticut federal bench during the politically charged decade leading into the Civil War. He continued the Ingersoll family's principal role in Connecticut legal and judicial life — his father Jonathan Jr. having served as Superior Court Judge and Lieutenant Governor, his elder brother Ralph in Congress and as US Minister to Russia."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Father of two sons who continued legal tradition","body":"Charles Anthony's two sons Charles Dennis Ingersoll (1843-1905, New York City lawyer) and Thomas Chester Ingersoll (1845-1884) continued the family legal tradition. The Ingersoll name extended across three generations of the New York and Philadelphia bars in addition to the original Connecticut branch. His brother Charles Jared Ingersoll (the Philadelphia cousin) had been the family progenitor of the Pennsylvania legal line."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Born 1798, died 1860 age sixty-two","body":"Charles Anthony Ingersoll was born in 1798 — likely a twin to his sister Harriet Ingersoll Voorhees who shares the same birth year. He died in 1860 at age sixty-two on the eve of the Civil War. His father Jonathan Ingersoll Jr. had been Lieutenant Governor of Connecticut at the time of his birth and continued in that role until his death in 1823."}],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","role":"student","notes":"Yale University AM 1827"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"military_service":[],"education":[],"career":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Charles Anthony Ingersoll","first_name":"Charles","last_name":"Ingersoll","middle_name":"Anthony","married_names":[],"gender":"male","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1779824780/judgecharlesingersoll_ydejnz.jpg"},"slug":"charles-ingersoll-1798"},"I01302":{"id":"I01302","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker_bool":false},"parents":{},"tags":[],"research_tags":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD5112","date_year":1839,"end_type":"death","end_year":1860,"children_ids":["HD5129","HD5130","HD5131"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"birth":{"year":1806,"month":6,"day":20,"city":"New York","county":"New York","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1877,"month":4,"day":9,"city":"New Haven","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States","age":70},"residence":{},"burial":{"plot_notes":"Grove Street Cemetery, New Haven CT"},"baptism":{},"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"military_service":[],"education":[],"career":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Henrietta Ingersoll","first_name":"Henrietta","last_name":"Ingersoll","maiden_name":"Sidell","married_names":["Ingersoll"],"gender":"female"},"slug":"henrietta-sidell-1806"},"HD0121":{"id":"HD0121","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1747,"month":4,"day":16,"city":"Ridgefield","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1823,"month":1,"day":12,"state":"Connecticut","country":"United States","age":75},"parents":{"father_id":"HD0115","mother_id":"I00079"},"political_offices":[{"title":"Member, Connecticut Council of Assistants","dates":"1792-1797"},{"title":"Judge, Connecticut Supreme Court of Errors","dates":"1792-1798"},{"title":"Superior Court Judge, Connecticut","dates":"1798-1801, 1811-1816"},{"title":"Lieutenant Governor, Connecticut","dates":"1816-1823","notes":"9th Lieutenant Governor; elected annually until death"}],"tags":["judge","lawyer","politician","yale_connection"],"sources":[],"gender":"male","notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["politics","law"],"notable_blurb":"Connecticut Lieutenant Governor 1816-1823, Superior Court Judge","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonathan_Ingersoll","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I01299","date_year":1786,"date_month":4,"date_day":1,"location_city":"New Haven","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1823,"children_ids":["HD5107","HD5108","HD5109","HD5110","HD5111","HD5112","HD5113","HD5114","HD5115","HD5116"]}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"place_overlap","related_id":"H01407","display_label":"Both buried Grove Street Cemetery, New Haven — Hooker descendants","link_text":"Dr. Worthington Hooker"}],"education":[{"degree":"graduate","school_name":"Yale College","graduation_year":1766,"institution_id":"INST022"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Jonathan Ingersoll Jr.","first_name":"Jonathan","last_name":"Ingersoll","suffix":"Jr.","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1766"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"politics","header":"Lieutenant Governor of Connecticut, 1816-1823","body":"Jonathan Ingersoll Jr. served as Lieutenant Governor of Connecticut from 1816 until his death in 1823 — the role making him a principal political figure of the early-Republic era in the state. The Lt Governor's office in Connecticut was a significant constitutional post during the years following the 1818 Constitution. His son Ralph I. Ingersoll later described him as 'a gentleman of great moral worth, and among the foremost in his profession.'"},{"number":2,"category":"law","header":"State Attorney, Superior Court Judge, then Lt Governor","body":"Jonathan rose through three principal Connecticut public-service offices in succession — first State Attorney, then a Judge of the Superior Court, then Lieutenant Governor. The progression took him from prosecutorial to judicial to political leadership across the late-eighteenth and early-nineteenth centuries. His judicial reputation rested on the same qualities of moral worth and professional standing that distinguished his political tenure."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Father of US Minister to Russia Ralph Ingersoll","body":"Jonathan's son Ralph I. Ingersoll (born February 8, 1789) followed him into the law and the public service — eight years in the United States Congress (1825-1833), State Attorney for twelve years, Connecticut Minister Plenipotentiary to the Russian court 1846-1848 under President Polk. The Ingersoll legal dynasty was one of the longest-running Connecticut family practices of the nineteenth century. A grandson Charles Roberts Ingersoll became Governor of Connecticut 1873-1877."}],"burial":{"plot_notes":"Grove Street Cemetery, New Haven CT"},"slug":"jonathan-ingersoll-jr-1747"},"I01299":{"id":"I01299","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker_bool":false},"parents":{},"tags":[],"research_tags":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD0121","date_year":1786,"date_month":4,"date_day":1,"location_city":"New Haven","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1823,"children_ids":["HD5107","HD5108","HD5109","HD5110","HD5111","HD5112","HD5113","HD5114","HD5115","HD5116"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"birth":{"year":1772,"country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1850,"age":78,"country":"United States"},"residence":{},"burial":{},"baptism":{},"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[],"quotes":[],"documents":[],